  "prompt": "How was the Alioth star named?",
  "response": "Alioth, the brightest star in the constellation Ursa Major (the Big Dipper), has a name with origins in Arabic astronomy. The name **Alioth** (also spelled **Alkaid** or **Alcor** in some contexts) is derived from the Arabic phrase **\"alyat al-hamal,\"** which translates to \"the tail of the sheep\" or \"the tail of the fat sheep.\" This reflects its position in the constellation, as it marks the end of the \"tail\" of the Great Bear or the handle of the Big Dipper.\n\nIn medieval Arabic astronomy, many stars were named based on their positions or roles in constellations, and these names were later Latinized and incorporated into Western astronomy. Alioth's name has thus been preserved and used in star catalogs and astronomical references ever since.",
